---
import { getCollection } from "astro:content";
import DecisionLog from "../../layouts/DecisionLog.astro";
import AdrSidebar from "../../components/AdrSidebar.astro";

// adrs.rsb.sh landing (ADR plan §5.6). On-demand so the host-routing middleware
// runs.
export const prerender = false;

const all = await getCollection("adrs");
const accepted = all.filter((a) => a.data.status === "accepted").length;
const deprecated = all.filter((a) => a.data.status === "deprecated").length;
const drafts = all.filter((a) => a.data.status === "draft").length;
const empty = all.length === 0;
---

<DecisionLog
  surface="Decisions"
  title="Decisions (ADRs)"
  description="Architecture decision records for the RSB ecosystem — the governing record of what was decided and why."
>
  <AdrSidebar slot="sidebar" />

  <h1 class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Decisions</h1>
  <p class="mt-4 max-w-prose text-neutral-600">
    Every load-bearing decision in the RSB ecosystem is recorded here as an
    Architecture Decision Record: the context that forced it, the decision itself,
    its consequences, and the alternatives that lost. Accepted ADRs carry a stable
    number and drive the <a href="https://standards.rsb.sh" class="underline hover:no-underline">standards</a> that released code cites.
  </p>

  {
    empty ? (
      <p class="mt-8 text-neutral-500">No decisions have been recorded yet.</p>
    ) : (
      <dl class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-x-10 gap-y-4 text-sm">
        <div>
          <dt class="text-neutral-500">Accepted</dt>
          <dd class="text-2xl font-semibold tabular-nums">{accepted}</dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt class="text-neutral-500">Deprecated</dt>
          <dd class="text-2xl font-semibold tabular-nums">{deprecated}</dd>
        </div>
        <div>
          <dt class="text-neutral-500">Drafts</dt>
          <dd class="text-2xl font-semibold tabular-nums">{drafts}</dd>
        </div>
      </dl>
    )
  }

  <section class="mt-12 max-w-prose">
    <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight">Reversibility</h2>
    <p class="mt-3 text-neutral-600">
      Every decision also carries a <span class="font-medium text-neutral-700">reversibility</span>
      tag, kept separate from its status. Status says where a decision sits in its
      life — draft, accepted, deprecated. Reversibility says something different:
      how forced the decision was, and how costly it would be to undo. The two are
      deliberately orthogonal — an accepted decision can still be reversible, and a
      superseded one may have been bedrock in its time.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-3 text-neutral-600">
      Tracking them apart keeps the strength of a decision explicit instead of
      buried in its prose, so a reader can tell at a glance whether they are looking
      at settled bedrock or a reasonable default that could still change.
    </p>

    <table class="mt-5 w-full border-collapse text-sm">
      <thead>
        <tr class="border-b border-neutral-200 text-left align-bottom">
          <th class="w-40 py-2 pr-4 font-medium text-neutral-500">Tag</th>
          <th class="py-2 font-medium text-neutral-500">What it means</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="align-top">
        <tr class="border-b border-neutral-100">
          <td class="py-3 pr-4">
            <span class="rounded bg-neutral-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-neutral-600">bedrock</span>
          </td>
          <td class="py-3 text-neutral-600">
            Over-determined — reversing it is a re-architecture, not a tweak. The
            decision was effectively forced, so it is treated as settled ground the
            rest of the ecosystem builds on.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-neutral-100">
          <td class="py-3 pr-4">
            <span class="rounded bg-neutral-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-neutral-600">hard to reverse</span>
          </td>
          <td class="py-3 text-neutral-600">
            A real commitment that can be undone, but expensively. Changing it later
            means unwinding work that was built on top of it.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-3 pr-4">
            <span class="rounded bg-neutral-100 px-1.5 py-0.5 text-xs uppercase tracking-wide text-neutral-600">reversible</span>
          </td>
          <td class="py-3 text-neutral-600">
            A reasonable default that could change cheaply if a concrete need
            appears. Recorded so the reasoning is kept, not because it is hard to
            move.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>
</DecisionLog>
